Note that birds described in this study are not complete bird community; in another paper (linked below) he cites 36 sp. in juniper site (other paper does not describe ponderosa site). Richness at each vert strata inferred from occurence figures for each species: if >3% of observations within a strata, species considered present at that strata. Species occurences within each strata were then summed to obtain estimate of richness for each strata. Bird observation methods are available in Balda 1970, which report surveys for juniper site but not ponderosa site; sampling effort for ponderosa site assumed approx. equal to his other sites: https://www.jstor.org/stable/pdf/1366011.pdf?refreqid=excelsior%3A2d15429156da6d756ae42ceb1dcf04f4

notes:
Birds low in the forest or in areas of sparse vegetation are more conspicuous than thosehigh in the canopy or in dense vegetation. Some foraging sites such as fan palm leaves are patchily distributed. Birds are easier to see in the dry season than in the wet season.
Searches were therefore made extensively and, as far as possible, at random through the forest. A conscious effort was made to search the entire canopy, particularly in the wet season.
